-- Apex Advantage — DPE Question Bank Expansion, Batch 3 of ~4 (v12)
--
-- Continues the expansion started in v10/v11 (72 -> 122 -> 172).
-- This batch completes Regulations (privileges category, +22, up to
-- 30), completes Airspace (+9, up to 30), completes Weather (+7, up
-- to 30), and adds most of the remaining Aircraft Systems questions
-- (+12, up to 24 of the 25 target -- the last one rolls into batch 4
-- alongside the rest of ADM).
--
-- Running total after this batch: 222 of ~250.
-- Remaining for batch 4: Aircraft Systems (+1) and ADM (+30) = ~31.
--
-- Checked against the existing 72, the 100 from v10/v11, and the free
-- "10 Questions DPEs Love to Ask" guide for topical overlap.
--
-- Run this in the Supabase SQL editor, after supabase-portal-schema-v11.

insert into public.dpe_questions (id, category, question, model_answer, common_mistakes, dpe_evaluating, acs_reference, real_world_application, is_scenario, scenario_order, sort_order) values

  -- ═══════════════════ REGULATIONS (privileges category, +22) ═══════════════════
  ('priv-9', 'privileges', 'You''re converging with another airplane at roughly the same altitude, off to your right, on a crossing path. Who has the right of way, and what''s your obligation?', 'The aircraft to the other''s right has the right of way — since the other aircraft is off to your right, they have the right of way and you must give way. Alter your course to the right and avoid passing in front of them, rather than assuming you have priority or waiting to see what they do.', 'Assuming right-of-way is based on which aircraft is faster, bigger, or arrived at the crossing point "first," rather than the actual regulatory rule based on relative position.', 'Whether you know and would actually apply the specific converging-course right-of-way rule, not a guess based on intuition.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.113.', 'Misjudging right-of-way in a converging scenario is a real, documented cause of near-midair collisions — knowing the rule cold means you don''t hesitate when it matters.', true, null, 8),
  ('priv-10', 'privileges', 'You''re in the pattern and another aircraft is on final approach to land while you''re about to take the runway for departure. Who has priority?', 'An aircraft on final approach to land, or actually landing, has the right of way over aircraft on the ground or aircraft in other phases of flight — you must give way and not take the runway until that aircraft has landed and is clear, or the tower (if towered) explicitly sequences you ahead.', 'Assuming an aircraft ready to depart has equal or greater priority than one already established on final, especially at a non-towered field.', 'Whether you know landing aircraft have priority over aircraft on the ground, and would actually hold rather than push to get out ahead.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.113.', 'This exact right-of-way conflict is common at busy non-towered airports, and getting it wrong is a real runway-incursion and collision risk.', true, null, 9),
  ('priv-11', 'privileges', 'What are the minimum safe altitudes over a congested area versus other than congested areas, and why does the distinction exist?', 'Over a congested area, you must remain at least 1,000 feet above the highest obstacle within a 2,000-foot horizontal radius of the aircraft. Over other than congested areas, you must remain at least 500 feet above the surface, except over open water or sparsely populated areas where you may not come closer than 500 feet to any person, vessel, vehicle, or structure. The distinction exists to give people and property on the ground added protection in more densely populated areas in the event of an emergency landing.', 'Applying the 500-foot rule everywhere without recognizing the higher 1,000-foot-above-obstacles standard applies specifically over congested areas.', 'Whether you know both standards and the reasoning behind having two different ones, not just one memorized number.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.119.', 'Flying too low over a congested area is both a real safety hazard and one of the more commonly enforced minimum-altitude violations.', false, null, 10),
  ('priv-12', 'privileges', 'What is the maximum indicated airspeed allowed below 10,000 feet MSL, and how does that change within the airspace near a busy Class C or Class D airport?', 'Below 10,000 feet MSL, the maximum indicated airspeed is 250 knots. Within 4 nautical miles of the primary airport of a Class C or Class D surface area, at or below 2,500 feet AGL, the maximum indicated airspeed drops further to 200 knots to help manage traffic conflicts near busy airports.', 'Knowing the general 250-knot limit but not knowing the additional 200-knot restriction that applies specifically near Class C/D surface areas.', 'Whether you know both the general and the more restrictive, airport-specific speed limit, since only knowing one leaves a real compliance gap.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.117.', 'The extra speed restriction near busy towered airports exists specifically to give pilots and controllers more time to see and avoid each other in a high-traffic-density area.', false, null, 11),
  ('priv-13', 'privileges', 'A friend with another airplane suggests you fly wingtip-to-wingtip for a few photos on your way back from a fly-in. Is this legal, and what do you need first?', 'Formation flight is legal but requires prior arrangement between the pilots in command of each aircraft involved — you cannot legally fly in formation with another aircraft based on a spontaneous, in-flight suggestion with no prior coordination.', 'Assuming a casual, in-the-moment agreement over the radio satisfies the "prior arrangement" requirement, rather than actual pre-flight coordination.', 'Whether you know formation flight has a specific, real prerequisite, not just general good judgment about following another aircraft closely.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.111.', 'An in-flight decision to "get some cool photos" without prior arrangement is both a regulatory violation and a real collision-risk shortcut.', true, null, 12),
  ('priv-14', 'privileges', 'Under what conditions, if any, can you legally drop an object from your aircraft in flight?', 'You may not drop an object in a way that creates a hazard to persons or property, but you can drop objects if reasonable precautions are taken to avoid injury or damage to persons or property — this is why activities like agricultural operations or approved parachute jump operations are conducted under specific procedures rather than being outright prohibited.', 'Assuming dropping anything from an aircraft is always illegal outright, rather than understanding the actual standard is about avoiding hazard, not an absolute prohibition.', 'Whether you know the actual regulatory standard rather than a vague sense that "you can''t drop things from planes."', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.15.', 'This regulation is exactly why organized activities like banner towing, agricultural spraying, and parachute operations can legally exist under proper precautions.', false, null, 13),
  ('priv-15', 'privileges', 'What does 14 CFR 91.13, the prohibition on careless or reckless operation, actually cover, and why is it sometimes called a "catch-all" regulation?', '91.13 prohibits operating an aircraft in a careless or reckless manner so as to endanger the life or property of another, without listing every specific prohibited action. It''s called a catch-all because the FAA can use it to enforce against behavior that endangers people or property even when no other more specific regulation directly addresses that exact action.', 'Assuming any regulatory violation must map to a specific, narrowly defined rule, missing that 91.13 exists precisely to cover genuinely dangerous behavior that isn''t otherwise specifically listed.', 'Whether you understand this regulation''s actual scope and purpose, since applicants sometimes haven''t considered it at all.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.13.', 'This is the regulation the FAA reaches for when a pilot''s judgment, not a specific technical violation, is the actual problem.', false, null, 14),
  ('priv-16', 'privileges', 'Your radio fails while inbound to a towered airport. The tower flashes a steady green light at you. What does that mean, and what should you do?', 'A steady green light while in flight means you''re cleared to land. Acknowledge by rocking your wings or flashing your landing light if practical, and proceed to land, continuing to watch for any additional light signals in case the situation changes.', 'Not knowing the light-gun signal system exists at all, or confusing the in-flight signal meanings with the different set of signals used for aircraft on the ground.', 'Whether you have a real backup communication method memorized for exactly this failure, not just an assumption that lost comm means you can''t land at a towered field.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.125.', 'Light gun signals are the actual, functioning backup for exactly this failure — a pilot who doesn''t know them is genuinely less prepared for a real lost-communications event at a towered airport.', true, null, 15),
  ('priv-17', 'privileges', 'At what cabin pressure altitude does a pilot need to start using supplemental oxygen, and how does that requirement change with duration and altitude?', 'For flights between 12,500 and 14,000 feet MSL cabin pressure altitude, the required minimum flight crew must use supplemental oxygen for that part of the flight exceeding 30 minutes. Above 14,000 feet MSL, the required minimum flight crew must use oxygen for the entire time at that altitude. Above 15,000 feet MSL, each occupant of the aircraft must be provided with supplemental oxygen.', 'Applying a single oxygen threshold regardless of duration, missing the specific 30-minute exception between 12,500 and 14,000 feet, or missing that the requirement expands to all occupants above 15,000 feet.', 'Whether you know the specific altitude and duration tiers rather than a single vague "use oxygen up high" answer.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.211.', 'Hypoxia symptoms can be subtle and easy to miss — knowing the exact legal (and physiologically sensible) thresholds is what keeps a high-altitude flight from becoming a hypoxia risk.', false, null, 16),
  ('priv-18', 'privileges', 'What preflight action is a pilot in command required to become familiar with before every flight, regardless of whether it''s a local flight or a cross-country?', 'The pilot in command must become familiar with all available information concerning that flight, which for a flight not in the vicinity of the departure airport includes weather reports and forecasts, fuel requirements, alternatives available if the planned flight can''t be completed, and any known traffic delays; for any flight, this also includes runway lengths at airports of intended use and aircraft performance data for takeoff and landing under the existing conditions.', 'Assuming this preflight-action requirement only applies to cross-country flights, missing that runway length and performance data checks apply to every flight, including local ones.', 'Whether you know this obligation applies broadly, and specifically what it requires even for a flight staying in the local area.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.103.', 'This regulation is the actual legal basis for the preflight planning habits — weather, performance numbers, runway lengths — that good pilots do out of genuine practice anyway.', false, null, 17),
  ('priv-19', 'privileges', 'When are occupants of an aircraft required to have their seatbelts fastened, and does that requirement differ for shoulder harnesses if the aircraft is equipped with them?', 'Each occupant must have their seatbelt fastened during taxi, takeoff, and landing at a minimum, and the pilot in command can require it be worn at other times too. If shoulder harnesses are installed, they must be worn by the required flight crew during takeoff and landing, unless the harness interferes with required duties, in which case it may be unfastened for that specific reason.', 'Assuming shoulder harness use is optional whenever installed, rather than knowing it''s specifically required for required crew during takeoff and landing when equipped.', 'Whether you know the specific requirement, not just the general expectation that seatbelts should be worn.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.107.', 'Shoulder harness use meaningfully reduces injury risk in an accident — knowing it''s an actual requirement, not just a suggestion, matters for every flight.', false, null, 18),
  ('priv-20', 'privileges', 'Can passengers use their phones or tablets during your flight, and does the same rule apply to your own use of an electronic flight bag app?', 'Portable electronic devices may generally be used, except the operator (or in this case, effectively the PIC for a private operation) must determine the device won''t cause interference with the navigation or communication system of the aircraft; devices like an EFB used by the pilot for navigation or charts are commonly accepted as not causing interference and are widely used, but the underlying standard — no interference with aircraft systems — applies to any device on board, not just passenger devices.', 'Assuming portable electronic device restrictions only apply to passengers and not to the pilot''s own EFB or tablet use.', 'Whether you understand the actual standard (no interference) applies universally on board, not selectively.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.21.', 'This is exactly why EFBs are broadly accepted for pilot use — the standard is about interference, not a blanket ban on electronics.', false, null, 19),
  ('priv-21', 'privileges', 'You''re flying near a glider being towed by another aircraft. In terms of right-of-way, what do you need to know about the tow plane, the glider, and your airplane?', 'An aircraft towing another has the right of way over other engine-driven aircraft, since the towing combination has limited maneuverability. More broadly, the general right-of-way hierarchy gives priority in this order: balloons have right of way over gliders, airships, and powered aircraft; gliders have right of way over airships and powered aircraft; airships have right of way over powered aircraft other than those towing.', 'Assuming a powered airplane always has priority over a glider or towing combination, when the actual hierarchy places less maneuverable aircraft and towing operations ahead of ordinary powered aircraft.', 'Whether you know this less-commonly-tested hierarchy in full, not just the basic converging-course rule.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.113.', 'Misjudging right-of-way around a towing operation or glider is a genuine risk, since these aircraft have real maneuverability limitations a powered airplane pilot needs to respect.', true, null, 20),
  ('priv-22', 'privileges', 'You''re acting as safety pilot for a friend practicing simulated instrument flight under a view-limiting device. What are the specific requirements for this operation to be legal?', 'The safety pilot must hold at least a private pilot certificate with the appropriate category and class rating for the aircraft being flown, and the aircraft must have functional dual controls, since the safety pilot is responsible for maintaining see-and-avoid separation while the flying pilot''s vision is restricted.', 'Assuming any passenger can serve as a safety pilot, or overlooking the dual-controls requirement for the aircraft itself.', 'Whether you know the specific certificate and equipment requirements, not just the general concept of "someone watches for traffic."', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.109.', 'A safety pilot who doesn''t meet the actual certificate requirement isn''t providing legal or genuinely reliable traffic separation for the flying pilot.', false, null, 21),
  ('priv-23', 'privileges', 'For logging purposes, what specifically qualifies a flight as "cross-country time," and how is that different from the practical, planning-focused idea of a cross-country flight you use every day?', 'For most logging purposes under 14 CFR 61.1, cross-country time requires a flight that includes a landing at a point other than the point of departure, using dead reckoning, pilotage, electronic navigation aids, radio aids, or other navigation systems to navigate — for most certificate and rating purposes there''s no minimum distance, though specific requirements, like the private pilot practical test''s cross-country experience, require the landing to be more than 50 nautical miles in straight-line distance from the original departure point.', 'Assuming every flight to another airport automatically counts as "cross-country time" for every regulatory purpose, without knowing some specific requirements have their own distance threshold layered on top of the general definition.', 'Whether you know the general logging definition and that certain specific requirements add their own distance threshold on top of it.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 61.1.', 'Misunderstanding this distinction can lead a pilot to believe a short hop to a nearby airport satisfies a specific cross-country experience requirement when it may not meet that requirement''s distance threshold.', false, null, 22),
  ('priv-24', 'privileges', 'You''re overtaking a slower aircraft flying the same direction as you, well above stall speed margin for both aircraft. What''s the correct way to pass?', 'The aircraft being overtaken has the right of way; the overtaking aircraft must alter course to the right to pass well clear, and neither aircraft''s pilot should assume the other has seen them — the overtaking aircraft carries the responsibility to maneuver, not the slower aircraft.', 'Assuming the faster aircraft can pass on whichever side is more convenient, rather than knowing the specific requirement to alter course to the right.', 'Whether you know the specific, correct direction for an overtaking maneuver, not just that you need to "stay clear."', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.113.', 'A wrong-side overtaking pass is a real, avoidable close-call risk, especially in a busy practice area or along a common cross-country corridor.', true, null, 23),
  ('priv-25', 'privileges', 'What is the difference between how "night" is defined for logging night flight time versus for the recency-of-experience requirement to carry passengers at night?', 'For logging night flight time, "night" is defined as the time between the end of evening civil twilight and the beginning of morning civil twilight. For the 61.57 recency requirement — three takeoffs and landings to remain current to carry passengers at night — "night" is defined more restrictively as one hour after sunset to one hour before sunrise, meaning some flight time that counts as "night" for logging doesn''t count toward night passenger-carrying currency.', 'Assuming a single definition of "night" applies to both logging and currency, when the regulations actually use two different windows.', 'Whether you know these are two distinct, non-interchangeable definitions, since conflating them can lead a pilot to believe they''re night-current when they''re not.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 1.1, 61.57.', 'A pilot who only tracks the civil-twilight definition might log flights as "night" without realizing they don''t actually satisfy the tighter one-hour-after-sunset currency window.', false, null, 24),
  ('priv-26', 'privileges', 'You''re at a towered airport and the weather is below basic VFR minimums, but you want to depart VFR anyway for a short local flight. Is there any option available?', 'You may request Special VFR if the airport is within a control zone that authorizes it, which allows operation clear of clouds with at least 1 statute mile flight visibility for fixed-wing aircraft, subject to ATC clearance and traffic; Special VFR at night requires the pilot to hold an instrument rating and the aircraft to be instrument-equipped.', 'Assuming Special VFR is available at every airport regardless of local restrictions, or forgetting the additional instrument-rating requirement for Special VFR operations at night.', 'Whether you know this option exists, its actual visibility standard, and its added restriction at night.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.157.', 'Special VFR is a real, legal option in genuinely marginal conditions, but only where authorized and only within its specific visibility and equipment limits.', true, null, 25),
  ('priv-27', 'privileges', 'What are the VFR weather minimums in Class G airspace below 1,200 feet AGL at night, and how do they compare to the daytime minimums for that same airspace?', 'By day, Class G airspace below 1,200 feet AGL requires 1 statute mile visibility and remaining clear of clouds. At night, the requirement steps up to 3 statute miles visibility with cloud clearance of 500 feet below, 1,000 feet above, and 2,000 feet horizontal — the same, more restrictive standard used for Class E airspace, since reduced visual references at night make the looser daytime Class G minimums genuinely unsafe.', 'Applying the same relaxed daytime Class G minimums to a night flight, missing that the standard becomes meaningfully more restrictive after dark.', 'Whether you know these minimums actually change by time of day in this specific airspace, not just by class.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.155.', 'Reduced visual references at night make the same weather genuinely riskier — this is exactly why the minimums tighten specifically for night operations in this airspace.', false, null, 26),
  ('priv-28', 'privileges', 'You''re approaching an unfamiliar airport with no operating control tower and no radio-published traffic pattern information. How do you determine the correct traffic pattern direction and altitude?', 'Absent other published information, standard traffic pattern turns are to the left, at a standard pattern altitude typically 1,000 feet AGL for light aircraft unless otherwise published; check the Chart Supplement, any segmented circle and traffic pattern indicators at the airport itself, and the CTAF for other traffic''s calls, since some airports do publish right-traffic patterns for specific runways due to obstacles or noise abatement.', 'Assuming standard left traffic always applies everywhere without checking for a specific published exception at that airport.', 'Whether you actually check available sources for a possible non-standard pattern rather than assuming the default everywhere.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.126.', 'Flying the wrong pattern direction at an airport with a published right-traffic exception is a real, avoidable conflict risk with other aircraft correctly following the actual local procedure.', true, null, 27),
  ('priv-29', 'privileges', 'What regulation requires you to comply with ATC instructions in controlled airspace, and what is the one general exception that allows you to deviate from that instruction?', 'Under 14 CFR 91.123, no pilot may deviate from an ATC clearance or instruction except in an emergency, or unless an amended clearance is obtained. The PIC emergency authority under 91.3(b) is the general exception — in an in-flight emergency requiring immediate action, the pilot in command may deviate from any rule, including an ATC instruction, to the extent required to meet that emergency.', 'Treating ATC instructions as always absolutely binding with no exception, or conversely treating the emergency exception as a broad excuse to deviate without a genuine emergency.', 'Whether you can cite the actual regulatory basis for both the general compliance requirement and its narrow, genuine exception.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.123, 91.3(b).', 'Knowing both the rule and its narrow exception matters — deviating without a genuine emergency is a real violation, but hesitating during an actual emergency because you''re unsure you''re "allowed" to deviate is its own hazard.', false, null, 28),
  ('priv-30', 'privileges', 'You occasionally fly your own airplane to visit clients as part of your regular sales job, though you''re paid a salary rather than paid specifically for the flying. Is this a compensation problem for a private pilot?', 'Generally not a violation — a private pilot may act as PIC of an aircraft used in connection with a business or employment, provided the flight is only incidental to that business or employment and the aircraft doesn''t carry passengers or property for compensation or hire as the actual purpose of the flight. The key is that flying isn''t the service being sold or compensated for; it''s a convenience incidental to your actual job.', 'Assuming any business-related use of a private pilot certificate is automatically prohibited compensation, without knowing the specific "incidental to business" allowance exists.', 'Whether you know this specific, real allowance, since applicants sometimes describe private pilot privileges as more restrictive than they actually are.', 'Area of Operation I, Task A — Pilot Qualifications (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 61.113.', 'This exact scenario — using your own airplane for work travel — is common among private pilots, and knowing where the actual legal line is protects you from an unnecessary certificate risk.', true, null, 29),

  -- ═══════════════════ AIRSPACE, completing to 30 (+9) ═══════════════════
  ('asp-22', 'airspace', 'What is the key legal difference between a Prohibited Area and a Restricted Area, in terms of whether you can ever transit through it?', 'A Prohibited Area bars aircraft flight entirely, at all times, without specific authorization from the controlling agency — there''s no "cold" status to rely on. A Restricted Area only prohibits entry while it''s actually active for its hazardous purpose; when inactive ("cold"), VFR transit is generally permitted, though you should still verify current status before relying on that.', 'Treating a Prohibited Area like a Restricted Area that might be "cold" and therefore transitable, when Prohibited Areas bar entry regardless of activity status.', 'Whether you know these are fundamentally different in their entry rule, not just different names for similar restricted airspace.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'Assuming a Prohibited Area might be safely transited if it "looks inactive" is a serious, real violation risk — unlike a Restricted Area, there''s no cold-status exception.', false, null, 21),
  ('asp-23', 'airspace', 'What is a Warning Area, and how is its legal status different from a domestic Restricted Area?', 'A Warning Area contains activity that may be hazardous to nonparticipating aircraft, typically established over international waters, where the FAA''s regulatory authority is more limited than over domestic airspace. As a result, a Warning Area functions more as an advisory to exercise caution rather than a domestically enforceable restriction in the same way a Restricted Area is.', 'Assuming a Warning Area carries the same enforceable restriction as a domestic Restricted Area, rather than recognizing its advisory nature over international waters.', 'Whether you understand why this airspace type exists and how its legal character differs due to its location.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'Understanding a Warning Area as advisory rather than a hard restriction still doesn''t mean ignoring it — the hazardous activity it warns about is genuinely real.', false, null, 22),
  ('asp-24', 'airspace', 'What is an Alert Area, and what should a VFR pilot expect and do differently when transiting one?', 'An Alert Area denotes airspace with a high volume of pilot training or unusual aerial activity; no specific clearance is required to transit it, but pilots should exercise heightened vigilance, since the volume and unpredictability of activity is meaningfully higher than typical airspace.', 'Treating an Alert Area as functionally identical to ordinary airspace with no need for extra vigilance, or conversely assuming it requires special clearance like a Restricted Area.', 'Whether you know the correct, moderate response — heightened awareness, not avoidance or a clearance requirement.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'A high volume of unpredictable traffic in an Alert Area is a real reason to be more vigilant, even though no special authorization is legally required.', false, null, 23),
  ('asp-25', 'airspace', 'What is a National Security Area (NSA), and is compliance with its published guidance mandatory or voluntary?', 'An NSA consists of airspace with defined vertical and lateral limits established at locations with a security or safety interest for the security or safety of ground facilities; pilots are requested to voluntarily avoid flying through an NSA, though the FAA can make flight through a specific NSA mandatory via NOTAM when circumstances warrant.', 'Assuming NSA guidance is always either purely voluntary or always mandatory, missing that it can shift to mandatory depending on the specific situation and an active NOTAM.', 'Whether you know this airspace type''s compliance status can change, and that checking current NOTAMs is what actually tells you which applies today.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'Treating "usually voluntary" as "always voluntary" without checking current NOTAMs could mean missing a genuinely mandatory restriction in effect that day.', false, null, 24),
  ('asp-26', 'airspace', 'You notice a charted parachute jump area along your planned VFR route. What is your responsibility as the transiting pilot?', 'Check for current activity at the jump area — through a briefing, NOTAMs, or monitoring the appropriate frequency — and be prepared to see and avoid parachutists and jump aircraft; charted jump areas indicate published, recurring activity, but actual timing of jumps isn''t continuous, so situational awareness rather than a blanket avoidance is the practical approach.', 'Ignoring a charted jump area entirely since it doesn''t carry the same regulatory weight as restricted or prohibited airspace, or assuming it''s always active.', 'Whether you treat a charted jump area as a real, practical hazard requiring active awareness, not just a chart symbol to note and forget.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'A parachutist descending into your flight path is a genuine collision hazard — checking for current activity before transiting a known jump area is a real, practical safety step.', true, null, 25),
  ('asp-27', 'airspace', 'What is the difference between a VFR corridor and a VFR transition route through Class B airspace?', 'A VFR corridor is airspace that allows unrestricted transit through a Class B airspace area, both laterally and vertically, without requiring an ATC clearance or even radio contact, since it''s effectively excluded from the Class B for that specific published corridor. A VFR transition route, by contrast, does require establishing radio contact and receiving an ATC clearance, just like any other Class B entry, though it defines a specific published path and altitude to simplify that process.', 'Assuming both terms describe the same thing, or that a VFR corridor still requires a clearance the way a transition route does.', 'Whether you know the actual, meaningful difference between these two specific, less commonly discussed Class B features.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'Assuming a VFR corridor requires the same clearance as a transition route could lead a pilot to unnecessarily delay a flight waiting for a clearance that isn''t actually required there.', false, null, 26),
  ('asp-28', 'airspace', 'How do the VFR weather minimums in Class G airspace below 1,200 feet AGL differ between day and night operations?', 'By day, the minimum is 1 statute mile visibility while remaining clear of clouds. At night, the requirement increases to 3 statute miles visibility with cloud clearance of 500 feet below, 1,000 feet above, and 2,000 feet horizontal — a meaningfully more restrictive standard reflecting the reduced visual references available after dark.', 'Applying the relaxed daytime Class G minimums to a night flight without recognizing the standard tightens considerably after dark.', 'Whether you know this specific day-versus-night distinction rather than a single, time-independent Class G minimum.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge) / 14 CFR 91.155.', 'Flying at the relaxed daytime Class G minimum after dark, when the actual legal (and sensible) standard is meaningfully stricter, is a real and avoidable compliance and safety gap.', false, null, 27),
  ('asp-29', 'airspace', 'What are the general differences between a security TFR, a disaster/hazard TFR, and a special event TFR, and why does knowing the type matter for how you plan around one?', 'A security TFR, such as one for Presidential or VIP movement, is typically strict, tightly enforced, and can appear with very little notice. A disaster or hazard TFR, such as one over a wildfire or accident scene, protects response aircraft and often has flexible, activity-driven boundaries. A special event TFR, such as one over a stadium during a major sporting event, is scheduled and published well in advance with fixed, known boundaries and times. Knowing the type helps you judge how much notice, flexibility, and enforcement rigor to expect.', 'Treating every TFR as functionally identical, without recognizing that the type affects how much advance notice you''ll have and how rigid its boundaries and enforcement actually are.', 'Whether you understand these categories differ meaningfully in practical planning terms, not just that "a TFR is a TFR."', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'A security TFR can appear with very little warning and is enforced strictly — treating it the same as a long-published stadium TFR is a real, avoidable risk for a pilot who assumes plenty of notice.', false, null, 28),
  ('asp-30', 'airspace', 'Where is ADS-B Out equipment generally required to operate, separate from the older Mode C transponder requirement?', 'ADS-B Out is generally required in Class A, B, and C airspace; above 10,000 feet MSL over the 48 contiguous United States, excluding airspace at and below 2,500 feet AGL; within 30 nautical miles of a Class B primary airport, from the surface up to 10,000 feet MSL, the same lateral area as the Mode C veil; and above the ceiling and within the lateral boundaries of Class B or Class C airspace up to 10,000 feet MSL. It largely mirrors, but doesn''t exactly duplicate, the older Mode C requirement areas.', 'Assuming ADS-B Out and Mode C transponder requirements apply in exactly identical areas, missing the specific altitude exclusions and boundaries unique to ADS-B Out.', 'Whether you know the current ADS-B Out requirement areas specifically, not just the older Mode C veil rule by itself.', 'Area of Operation I, Task E — National Airspace System (Knowledge).', 'Flying into ADS-B-required airspace without a functioning, properly configured ADS-B Out system is a real, modern compliance gap distinct from the older transponder-only requirement.', false, null, 29),

  -- ═══════════════════ WEATHER, completing to 30 (+7) ═══════════════════
  ('wx-24', 'weather', 'What specific criteria trigger a Convective SIGMET, and how is that different from the more general severe-weather information in a regular SIGMET?', 'A Convective SIGMET is issued specifically for severe or embedded thunderstorms, a line of thunderstorms, thunderstorms affecting 40% or more of an area at least 3,000 square miles, hail three-quarters of an inch or greater, wind gusts of 50 knots or greater at the surface, or tornadoes — it''s a more specific, higher-threshold product focused purely on convective activity, whereas a general SIGMET can cover a broader range of hazards like severe turbulence or icing unrelated to thunderstorms.', 'Treating "SIGMET" and "Convective SIGMET" as the same product, missing that Convective SIGMET has its own specific, higher-threshold triggering criteria.', 'Whether you know the specific triggering criteria for this particular product, not just that severe-weather advisories exist in general.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Knowledge).', 'A Convective SIGMET represents a genuinely serious, specifically-defined threshold of thunderstorm activity — treating it with the same level of urgency as a routine AIRMET understates the actual hazard.', false, null, 23),
  ('wx-25', 'weather', 'What makes freezing rain a more hazardous icing encounter than typical structural icing in clouds, and what should you do if you encounter it?', 'Freezing rain involves supercooled large droplets that fall through a shallow warm layer aloft before refreezing on contact with a colder aircraft surface, producing rapid, heavy ice accretion that can quickly overwhelm an aircraft''s ice protection systems and exceed what light aircraft, and even many certified deicing systems, are designed to handle. Encountering it calls for an immediate exit from the precipitation — a climb, descent, or reversal — rather than attempting to continue through it.', 'Treating freezing rain the same as ordinary structural icing in clouds, rather than recognizing it as a substantially faster, more severe accretion hazard requiring an immediate exit.', 'Whether you recognize freezing rain as a distinctly more urgent hazard, not just another variety of the icing already discussed elsewhere.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Risk Management).', 'Freezing rain has been a factor in serious icing-related accidents specifically because its accretion rate can outpace a pilot''s decision-making time if not recognized and exited immediately.', true, null, 24),
  ('wx-26', 'weather', 'What is a microburst, and what specific wind signature would alert you to one on approach?', 'A microburst is a small-scale, intense downdraft that spreads out in all directions upon reaching the surface, capable of producing severe wind shear over a short distance and time. On approach, the telltale signature is an increasing headwind followed by a rapid shift to a decreasing headwind or tailwind as you pass through the outflow, along with a significant, rapid change in vertical speed and pitch attitude required to maintain your approach path.', 'Only associating microbursts with visible weather like a thunderstorm nearby, missing the specific headwind-then-tailwind wind-shift signature that identifies one in progress.', 'Whether you know the specific wind signature to recognize a microburst in progress, not just that they''re associated with convective weather generally.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Risk Management).', 'Recognizing the specific wind-shift signature of a microburst, and executing an immediate go-around, is what separates a survivable encounter from a genuinely catastrophic one.', false, null, 25),
  ('wx-27', 'weather', 'You notice lenticular clouds near mountainous terrain along your route. What do they indicate, and what should that tell you about turbulence?', 'Lenticular clouds, lens-shaped and often stacked, form on the downwind side of mountains where stable air flows over terrain and creates a standing mountain wave; they''re a strong visual indicator of possible severe turbulence and strong up and downdrafts in that area, even in otherwise clear, seemingly calm-looking air.', 'Not recognizing lenticular clouds as a specific visual warning sign, or assuming smooth-looking air near mountains means no turbulence risk.', 'Whether you can read this specific visual cue and connect it to a real, sometimes severe, hazard that isn''t obvious from calm-looking surrounding air.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Knowledge).', 'Mountain wave turbulence associated with lenticular clouds can be severe enough to exceed a light aircraft''s structural limits — recognizing the visual cue before entering the area matters.', true, null, 26),
  ('wx-28', 'weather', 'What is a squall line, and how is the hazard it presents different from an isolated, individual thunderstorm cell?', 'A squall line is a narrow band of active thunderstorms, often forming ahead of a fast-moving cold front, that can extend for a long distance and offers few gaps to route around compared to isolated cells. Unlike a single storm you might deviate around, a squall line''s continuous or near-continuous structure can force a much larger detour or an outright cancellation, since there may be no safe gap to thread through.', 'Treating a squall line like a single storm you can simply deviate slightly around, rather than recognizing its extended, often gap-free structure as a fundamentally different planning problem.', 'Whether you understand why a squall line often demands a much larger route change or cancellation, not just a minor deviation.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Attempting to thread a gap in a squall line that isn''t actually there is a documented, serious risk — recognizing the difference from an isolated cell changes the entire decision.', false, null, 27),
  ('wx-29', 'weather', 'What specifically defines a "ceiling" in a METAR, and why doesn''t a scattered cloud layer count as one?', 'A ceiling is defined as the height of the lowest layer of clouds reported as broken or overcast, or the vertical visibility into an indefinite obscuration — a scattered layer, by definition covering less than half the sky, doesn''t meet the broken or overcast threshold and therefore isn''t reported as a ceiling, even if it''s the lowest cloud layer present.', 'Treating any reported cloud layer, including scattered, as the "ceiling," rather than knowing the specific broken/overcast (or obscuration) threshold that actually defines one.', 'Whether you know the precise definition rather than a loose, generally-correct-sounding answer.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Knowledge).', 'Correctly identifying whether a ceiling actually exists, versus just a scattered layer, directly affects whether a flight legally and practically meets VFR cloud clearance requirements.', false, null, 28),
  ('wx-30', 'weather', 'What is the standard temperature lapse rate, and how can you use it along with the temperature/dew point spread to quickly estimate cloud base height without a chart?', 'The standard atmosphere temperature lapse rate is approximately 2 degrees Celsius per 1,000 feet. A commonly used quick estimate for convective cloud base takes the surface temperature/dew point spread in degrees Celsius, divides by roughly 2.5, and multiplies by 1,000 feet to approximate the cloud base height above the surface — a useful mental-math check during preflight planning or in flight.', 'Not knowing this estimation method exists, relying entirely on a forecast cloud base number without a way to sanity-check it using current surface conditions.', 'Whether you have a practical, quick mental tool for estimating cloud base, not just dependence on a forecast product alone.', 'Area of Operation I, Task C — Weather Information (Knowledge).', 'This quick mental estimate lets you sanity-check a forecast cloud base against current, actual surface conditions in real time, rather than relying purely on an aging forecast number.', false, null, 29),

  -- ═══════════════════ AIRCRAFT SYSTEMS (+12, one remaining for batch 4) ═══════════════════
  ('acsys-13', 'aircraft-systems', 'How does a typical mechanical stall warning system actually detect an approaching stall, and what is it really sensing?', 'A mechanical stall warning system typically uses a spring-loaded tab or vane on the leading edge of the wing that responds to the changing airflow and stagnation point position as angle of attack increases, triggering a horn or light before the critical angle of attack is reached; some aircraft instead use an electronic angle-of-attack sensor. Either way, it''s fundamentally sensing angle of attack, or a proxy for it, not a specific airspeed.', 'Describing the stall warning as an airspeed-based system, missing that it''s actually detecting angle of attack or airflow changes associated with it, which is why it can trigger at different airspeeds depending on load factor.', 'Whether you connect the stall warning system to the same angle-of-attack concept tested elsewhere, rather than treating it as a simple low-airspeed alarm.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'Understanding the stall warning as an angle-of-attack indicator, not an airspeed alarm, is why it correctly triggers at a higher airspeed during an accelerated stall in a steep turn.', false, null, 12),
  ('acsys-14', 'aircraft-systems', 'What is the difference between plain flaps and Fowler flaps in terms of how they affect lift and drag, and how does electric versus manual actuation change how you manage them in the cockpit?', 'Plain flaps simply hinge downward from the wing''s trailing edge, primarily increasing drag with a more modest lift increase; Fowler flaps extend aft and then deflect downward, increasing wing area as well as camber, producing a larger lift increase for a given drag penalty compared to plain flaps. Electric flap systems are typically selected to a setting and move automatically to that position, while manual systems, such as a Johnson bar, require the pilot to physically position and hold or lock the flap handle, giving more direct, immediate tactile feedback but demanding more physical attention during a busy phase of flight.', 'Assuming all flap types produce essentially the same lift-to-drag trade-off, or not knowing manual flap systems require different physical handling than electric ones.', 'Whether you understand both the aerodynamic difference between flap types and the practical cockpit workflow difference between actuation methods.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'Knowing your specific aircraft''s flap type and actuation method affects both your landing performance expectations and your actual in-cockpit workflow during approach and landing.', false, null, 13),
  ('acsys-15', 'aircraft-systems', 'What is the actual purpose of the trim system, and what would happen if a trim runaway occurred in flight?', 'Trim relieves the control pressure needed to hold a given attitude or airspeed, reducing pilot workload — it is not a primary flight control and doesn''t by itself change the aircraft''s attitude the way the elevator does when you move the yoke. A trim runaway, where trim continues moving on its own, would produce increasing control pressure in the opposite direction as the trim moves further from the needed setting, requiring the pilot to physically overpower it and address the malfunction, such as by pulling the trim circuit breaker if electrically actuated.', 'Describing trim as a primary flight control that directly flies the aircraft, rather than understanding it as a workload-reducing pressure-relief system.', 'Whether you understand trim''s actual role well enough to correctly reason through what a trim malfunction would feel like and how to respond.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'A pilot who misunderstands trim as a primary control might mishandle an actual trim runaway, when the correct response is to recognize and physically overpower or disable it, not chase it with more trim input.', true, null, 14),
  ('acsys-16', 'aircraft-systems', 'What are the primary flight controls in a typical light aircraft connected to physically, and what might a control cable or pushrod failure feel like in flight?', 'Primary flight controls are typically connected through a system of cables, pushrods, and bellcranks running from the cockpit controls to the ailerons, elevator, and rudder. A cable or pushrod failure would likely present as a sudden loss of effectiveness or complete disconnect in that specific control axis — for example, an aileron input producing no roll response — while the other, unaffected control axes would continue working normally.', 'Assuming a control system failure would affect all flight controls simultaneously, rather than recognizing that a specific cable or pushrod failure typically isolates to just that one control axis.', 'Whether you understand the mechanical connection well enough to reason through what a specific failure would actually feel like, not just that "the controls" might fail generally.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'Recognizing that a control failure is isolated to one axis, rather than assuming total control loss, is what lets a pilot actually assess what''s still flyable and land using the remaining functional controls.', false, null, 15),
  ('acsys-17', 'aircraft-systems', 'How does the cabin heating system in a typical piston single actually generate heat for the cabin?', 'Most piston singles use a heat exchanger, often called a heater muff, wrapped around a section of the exhaust system; outside air is ducted through the muff, picks up heat from the exhaust pipe without directly mixing with exhaust gases, and is then routed into the cabin. The heat source is entirely the hot exhaust pipe surface, not any dedicated electric or combustion heater.', 'Assuming the cabin heat comes from an electric or dedicated fuel-burning heater, rather than knowing it''s heat exchanged from the exhaust system.', 'Whether you understand the actual heat source and pathway, which is directly relevant to why a cracked heat exchanger is a genuine carbon monoxide risk.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'Understanding that cabin heat comes from air passing near, not through, the exhaust system is exactly why a cracked heat exchanger creates a real carbon monoxide intrusion risk.', false, null, 16),
  ('acsys-18', 'aircraft-systems', 'What is the difference in role between the battery and the alternator in a typical light aircraft electrical system, and what determines how long you could keep flying on battery power alone after an alternator failure?', 'The battery''s primary role is providing power for engine starting and serving as a backup source; the alternator''s role is to supply the aircraft''s electrical loads during normal operation and recharge the battery. After an alternator failure, how long you can keep flying on the battery alone depends on the battery''s remaining charge and capacity, and how much electrical load you''re drawing — which is exactly why shedding non-essential electrical load after an alternator failure meaningfully extends your available time.', 'Treating the battery and alternator as interchangeable power sources rather than understanding their distinct roles, or not connecting load-shedding to actually extending battery-only flight time.', 'Whether you understand this relationship well enough to make a real, informed decision about load-shedding and remaining flight time after an alternator failure.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Knowing that reducing electrical load genuinely extends your battery-only time is a real, actionable piece of knowledge in an alternator-failure emergency, not just trivia about how the system works.', true, null, 17),
  ('acsys-19', 'aircraft-systems', 'What is the difference between a circuit breaker and a fuse, and what is the generally accepted guidance on resetting a popped circuit breaker in flight?', 'A circuit breaker is a resettable protective device that opens the circuit when current exceeds a safe threshold, and can typically be reset by the pilot; a fuse performs the same protective function but is a one-time device that must be physically replaced once it blows, which isn''t practical in flight. General guidance is that a circuit breaker may be reset once, if the circuit is important enough to the flight to be worth trying, but if it pops again, it shouldn''t be reset again, since that suggests a genuine, ongoing fault rather than a momentary anomaly.', 'Assuming a popped circuit breaker can simply be reset repeatedly until it stays in, rather than recognizing a second trip as a signal of a real fault that shouldn''t be forced.', 'Whether you know the accepted "reset once" guidance and the reasoning behind not repeatedly resetting a breaker that keeps tripping.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Risk Management).', 'Repeatedly resetting a circuit breaker that keeps tripping risks an electrical fire or further damage — respecting the "reset once" guidance is a real safety practice, not overcaution.', false, null, 18),
  ('acsys-20', 'aircraft-systems', 'What does an impulse coupling on a magneto do during engine start, and why does the engine sound and behave differently while starting compared to when it''s running normally?', 'An impulse coupling temporarily retards ignition timing and then releases suddenly, producing a strong, well-timed spark at the low RPM of engine cranking, when a normally-timed spark would be too weak and too early relative to piston position to reliably start the engine; once the engine reaches running RPM, the impulse coupling disengages and normal magneto timing takes over.', 'Assuming ignition timing works identically during starting and normal running, without knowing the impulse coupling exists specifically to solve the low-RPM starting problem.', 'Whether you understand why starting behavior is genuinely different from running behavior, and the specific mechanism that makes that possible.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'Understanding the impulse coupling explains the distinct "whirring" or clicking sound some engines make during cranking, and why a healthy start doesn''t mean normal-timed ignition throughout.', false, null, 19),
  ('acsys-21', 'aircraft-systems', 'Where does a carburetor heat system draw its heated air from, and why does applying carb heat typically cause a temporary RPM drop even when there was no actual ice present?', 'Carburetor heat routes unfiltered air heated by passing near the exhaust system into the carburetor intake, bypassing the normal filtered induction air; this heated air is less dense than the normal intake air, which reduces engine power slightly and causes a temporary RPM drop purely from the reduced air density, independent of whether ice was actually present or being melted.', 'Interpreting any RPM drop after applying carb heat as evidence that ice was present, without knowing that a smaller drop is expected purely from the reduced air density even with no ice at all.', 'Whether you understand the actual cause of the expected RPM behavior, since misreading it can lead to either false reassurance or false alarm about actual icing.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge).', 'A pilot who understands the expected baseline RPM drop can better distinguish a normal response from the larger, sustained rise in RPM that indicates ice was actually present and is now melting.', false, null, 20),
  ('acsys-22', 'aircraft-systems', 'Why do some more sophisticated light aircraft electrical systems separate an "essential" bus from a "non-essential" or avionics bus, and what does that mean during a partial electrical problem?', 'Splitting the electrical system into an essential bus (critical flight instruments, primary radios) and a non-essential or avionics bus (secondary avionics, less critical accessories) lets a pilot shed the non-essential bus entirely during a partial electrical problem, preserving power for the truly critical systems on the essential bus for longer, rather than having every electrical item draw from a single, undifferentiated pool.', 'Assuming all electrical items in the aircraft draw from a single, undifferentiated system with no way to selectively shed lower-priority loads.', 'Whether you know your own aircraft''s bus architecture well enough to actually execute a smart, prioritized load-shedding plan rather than a generic "turn things off" response.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Knowing which bus your critical instruments are actually on is what makes a real load-shedding decision effective during an electrical problem, rather than guessing which switches matter most.', false, null, 21),
  ('acsys-23', 'aircraft-systems', 'You extend flaps on final approach and the aircraft yaws and rolls unexpectedly toward one side. What might be happening, and how do you respond?', 'This suggests an asymmetric flap deployment — one flap extended while the other didn''t, or extended to a different position — which changes lift and drag unevenly between the wings and produces the yaw and roll you''re feeling; retract the flaps back to the last known symmetric position if possible, adjust with aileron and rudder to counteract the asymmetry, and plan for a go-around and a landing using reduced or no flaps rather than continuing an approach with an unpredictable flap condition.', 'Continuing to extend or retract flaps further while trying to diagnose the problem, rather than returning to a known-good, symmetric configuration and planning a modified landing.', 'Whether you correctly identify an asymmetric flap condition from its actual handling signature and respond with a safe, known configuration rather than continuing to experiment.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Risk Management).', 'An asymmetric flap failure is a genuine handling emergency close to the ground — recognizing the signature quickly and returning to a known configuration is what keeps the approach controllable.', true, null, 22),
  ('acsys-24', 'aircraft-systems', 'How reliable are fuel quantity gauges required to be under the certification standards, and what does that mean for how you should actually determine your fuel on board before a flight?', 'Fuel quantity gauges are only required to be accurate when indicating zero fuel remaining in that tank; at other readings, they''re not certified to a precise standard, which is why POHs and instructors emphasize visually verifying fuel quantity during preflight and tracking fuel by calculated burn rate in flight, rather than treating the gauge reading alone as a precise, trustworthy number throughout the flight.', 'Trusting the fuel gauge as precisely accurate at any reading above zero, rather than knowing its only certified accuracy point is empty.', 'Whether you know this specific, often-surprising certification standard and its real practical implication for how you actually track fuel.', 'Area of Operation I, Task G — Operation of Systems (Knowledge and Risk Management).', 'Relying on a fuel gauge reading that "looks fine" instead of a visual check and calculated burn tracking is a documented contributor to fuel exhaustion accidents.', false, null, 23);
